### **Data and Methods** {data-width=500}

#### Research Design

- Longitudinal study (BIBO Study) 
- Microbiota sampling at 10 and 14 weeks of age
- Two groups: Chilcare attendance (n = 49) vs control (n = 49)

#### Data

- Microbial determination of three phylogenetic levels with the Human Intestinal Tract Chip (HITChip)
- Covariates: Amount of breastfeeding (number of feedings/day) and age
- Data was treated as compositional (centered-log-ratio-transformation)
    
#### Statistical Analyses:
- PCA (Aitchison distance)
- PERMANOVA (Aitchison distance)
- Hierarchical Linear Mixed Models (Gaussian family)
- Bayesian Hierarchical Generalized Linear Models (Generalized normal distribution)
- Randfom Forest Classification




## Footer row {data-height=15} 

### Results {data-width=45}

- There was no effect of childcare attendance on overall composition (A).
- Slight decrease in alpha diversity in the childcare attendance group (B).
- Small differences in relative abundances between the groups after controlling for age and breastfeeding (C). 
- High variation: Many infants showed an opposite trend compared to the group level effect.


### Conclusion {data-width=45}
- Childcare attendance did not lead to a uniform change in gut microbiota composition or disrupt early development of the microbial ecosystem.



